Absolutely! Here's a detailed step-by-step guide along with a complete example of how to automatically generate a Table of Contents (ToC) in a LaTeX document, leveraging the power of `\tableofcontents` command, `\addcontentsline` for manual inclusion, and packages like `tocbibind` and `hyperref` for comprehensive control:

```latex
\documentclass[12pt, a4paper]{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}

% Load necessary packages
\usepackage{hyperref} % For clickable ToC and cross-referencing
\usepackage{tocbibind} % To include bibliography and list of figures/tables in ToC
\usepackage{bookmarks, blindtext} % For bookmarks and dummy text

\title{Example Document with Auto-generated ToC}
\author{Author Name}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\tableofcontents  % Generates the automatic Table of Contents

\newpage  % To start the content with a fresh page after ToC

\section{Introduction}
\blinddocument  % Fill with dummy text

\section{Methodology}
\blinddocument

\subsection{Sub-method A}
\blinddocument

\subsection{Sub-method B}
\blinddocument

% Manually adding an entry to ToC without a section/chapter
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{\protect\numberline{3.5}List of Acronyms}
\listofacronyms % Assuming you have a listofacronyms environment/list

\section{Results}
\blinddocument

\chapter{A Detailed Chapter}
\section{Chapter Section}

% Automatically numbered ToC continues with chapters and sections recursively

\section{Conclusion}
\blinddocument

\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{References} % Manual inclusion of References in ToC
\bibliographystyle{plain}
\bibliography{mybibfile} % Assuming you have a .bib file

\section{List of Figures and Tables}
\listoffigures % And list of tables: \listoftables

\end{document}

**Key points**: The `\tableofcontents` command is run before including any section with content, ensuring it captures all sections/subsections/chapters. The `hyperref` package ensures the ToC is clickable and properly linked. The `tocbibind` package ensures bibliography and lists are included in the ToC. The `\addcontentsline` command is used for special cases where you need an entry without a sectional unit. The above example covers all these aspects comprehensively. 

By compiling this document with `pdflatex` (or `lualatex`/`xelatex`), you'll get a LaTeX document with a fully automatic, clickable, and well-structured Table of Contents.

